<HL>
   Initial State Jobless Claims
   Increased in Latest Week
</HL>
<DATE>
06/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
ECONOMIC AND MONETARY INDICATORS (EMI)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Initial claims for regular state
unemployment benefits rose to a seasonally adjusted 356,000
in the week ended May 26 from 342,000 the previous week, the
Labor Department said.
   The number of people receiving regular state benefits in
the week ended May 19 was a seasonally adjusted 2,397,000, or
2.3% of those covered by unemployment insurance, from
2,429,000 the previous week, when the insured unemployment
rate was also 2.3%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Counting all state and federal benefit programs, the
number of people receiving unemployment benefits in the week
ended May 19 fell to 2,247,900 from 2,330,400 a week earlier.
These figures aren't seasonally adjusted.
</TEXT>
