<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   New Civil-Rights Bill
   Won't Mandate Quotas
</HL>
<DATE>
06/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
</IN>
<LP>
   In "The 1990 Civil Rights Bill Is Wrong" (editorial page,
May 4) Abigail Thernstrom misrepresents the intent and the
effect of the Civil Rights Act of 1990. This bill corrects a
series of Supreme Court decisions made in June 1989 that
narrowly interpret equal-employment opportunity and
civil-rights laws. It does not mandate or "invite" quotas, as
Ms. Thernstrom asserts.
   For 18 years, employers had the burden of showing that
employment practices with a "disparate impact" (that operated
to exclude minorities and women disproportionately) are
required by business necessity. The Supreme Court's June 1989
decision in Wards Cove Packing Co. v. Atonio razed this
settled law and placed an extreme and unprecedented burden on
discrimination victims by making them prove specifically the
practice that ultimately led to discrimination. The Civil
Rights Act of 1990 sends the message that employment
discrimination is never acceptable and returns the burden of
justifying any business practice that results in disparate
impact to the employer.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Furthermore, on May 2 the bill was amended so that
employers can prove business necessity by showing that a
challenged practice "bears a substantial and demonstrable
relationship to effective job performance." In other words,
employment decisions made to create an effective work force
are justifiable under the Civil Rights Act of 1990. Thus, the
law allows employers to hire the best-qualified people and
does not place us on the crest of the slippery slope of
hiring and promotion quotas as envisioned by Ms. Thernstrom.
   Ms. Thernstrom says the Civil Rights Act of 1990 may
"deliver a message that minority groups amount to separate
nations and separate nations require distinct treatment." To
the contrary, the act seeks to prevent dangerous separate
treatment, which is in part what triggered Wards Cove. In
this case, Frank Atonio and other salmon-cannery workers,
mostly Filipinos and Alaska Natives, sued their employer for
hiring practices that excluded them from the better-paying
jobs and favored whites. For instance, the Wards Cove Packing
Co. maintained racially separate hiring pools and job
categories. The company's dormitories and cafeterias
generally separated white employees from nonwhite employees.
"Separate" and "distinct" treatment is precisely what the act
seeks to eliminate by providing discrimination victims a
reasonable chance of proving discrimination.
   The Civil Rights Act of 1990 also addresses other
intolerable inconsistencies created by the Supreme Court's
June 1989 decisions. The law ensures that job bias based on
gender and race is always illegal, that statutes of
limitation are applied fairly and consistently, and that
victims of intentional discrimination can recover damages.
   If passed, the Civil Rights Act of 1990 will enable this
country to continue to eradicate workplace discrimination by
restoring the well-tested legal standards used to prove
employment discrimination for the past 25 years.
   Antonia Hernandez
   President and General Counsel
   Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund
   Los Angeles
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900608-0156
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900608-0156.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   It Seems That What They'll Need
   Is a Good Junk-Bond Salesman
   ----
   By Adi Ignatius
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   SHENZHEN, China -- Businessmen, step right up] The
People's Republic of China has just the deal for you.
   In a special one-time offer, the Chinese government is
selling state-owned Xinle Wood Furniture Factory to the
highest bidder, Chinese or foreign. Xinle Wood is a furniture
maker that lost a bundle in 1988 and then a bunch more in
1989.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   There's more. Whoever buys the factory also inherits its
33 employees. For life. That's because when you tap into the
socialist system, you must play by its rules. And
state-employed workers don't get fired, even if there's no
work to do. On a recent afternoon, three of the 33 paid
employees were on the job: two women idly chatting in a
corner and a young man hammering nails into some plywood.
   Still interested? The successful bidder also can continue
Xinle Wood's product line. In fact, according to the rules,
the winning bidder MUST stick to the stuff that got Xinle
Wood where it is today: cheap desks and wardrobes, and bed
frames with headboards sporting two big pink hearts on a
baby-blue background.
   The offer ends soon, so send in those bids. The government
of Shenzhen, a Chinese "special economic zone" bordering Hong
Kong, is hoping to pull in roughly $3 million for the
factory.
   In addition to Xinle Wood, the government is selling three
other struggling state-owned enterprises. There's Xinle Metal
Products Co., also in the red, and two factories barely
breaking even: Xinle Bedding Supplies and Xinle Sofa Co.
   A word of caution: If a bidder's goal is to help hasten
the privatization of China's state-run economy, it's best to
keep that under one's hat. The P-word has become taboo in
China since the lethal suppression of last year's student-led
protest movement in Beijing.
   Nonetheless, the Shenzhen government is touting the
planned sales as a bold new step in China's economic-reform
program. Guo Weiping, the bureaucrat overseeing the sale
offer, calls it "industrial adjustment." Put another way, the
four factories' state-run parent, Shenzhen Decoration &amp;
Construction Industrial Co., gets to dump a handful of money
losers.
   To date, no U.S. company has made a bid since the sale
offer was announced April 23. But Shenzhen is hopeful. "We
definitely welcome U.S. investment," says Mr. Guo, adding as
a tease, "The first companies to jump on such an offer are
sure to succeed."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
