<HL>
   Traffic Rises for Two Airlines
</HL>
<DATE>
06/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C5
</SO>
<CO>
   AMR LUV
</CO>
<IN>
AIRLINES (AIR)
</IN>
<LP>
   FORT WORTH, Texas -- Two Texas-based air carriers reported
increases in May traffic.
   American Airlines, a unit of AMR Corp., said traffic rose
3.5%, to 6.40 billion revenue passenger miles from 6.18
billion in the year-earlier period.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A revenue passenger mile is one paying passenger flown one
mile.
   American's load factor, or percentage of seats filled,
fell to 61.9% from 62.8%, the Fort Worth company said.
   Southwest Airlines, Dallas, said it flew 854.3 million
revenue passenger miles in May, up 7.3% from 796.5 million in
the year-earlier period. Load factor for the month was 61.1%,
compared with 61.6%.
