<HL>
   International:
   U.S., Allies Ease
   Technology Curbs
   On Eastern Sales
</HL>
<DATE>
06/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP JAPAN FREST
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
COMMERCE DEPARTMENT (COM)
</GV>
<LP>
   PARIS -- In a further sign of warming East-West relations,
the U.S. and its 16 main Western allies agreed to ease their
41-year-old embargo on sales of high-technology products to
the East bloc.
   The agreement, reached at a two-day meeting of allied
officials here, authorizes a major liberalization of
technology-trade restrictions to the East. All export curbs
will end for most Western personal computers and other
commonly available technology products. More important, the
allies agreed to greatly reduce restrictions on sales of
mainframe computers, telephone exchanges, machine tools and
other more-sophisticated products.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The accord, based on a Bush administration proposal
announced May 2, opens the door to East-West trade in a wide
range of technology products. As one indication of the
accord's importance, U.S. officials said the products
involved currently make up about $45 billion, or 30%, of
annual U.S. technology exports around the world. The East
hasn't enough hard currency to place orders anywhere near
that volume. But Western businesses expect the accord to
allow a gradual rise in direct sales to the East, and an
immediate surge in East-West technology joint ventures.
   Many Western businesses cheered the accord, even though
some had urged even greater liberalization. "We are very
pleased," said a spokesman in Armonk, N.Y., for International
Business Machines Corp. "This represents substantial
progress." An official of the West German Industry Federation
called the accord "a step forward" in East-West trade.
   The pact also was attacked by some U.S. conservatives.
This "ill-advised" accord will "enable the Soviets for far
less {effort} to field far more capable military forces in
the future," said Frank Gaffney Jr., a former Pentagon
official who heads the Center for Security Policy, a
conservative Washington think tank.
   Before sales can begin, the agreement has to be
implemented by laws or rules in each of the 17 countries
participating in the trade organization, called the
Coordinating Committee on Multilateral Export Controls, or
Cocom. The 17 countries are the U.S., Japan, Australia, and
all of the West European countries except Iceland that belong
to the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher, who helped craft the
U.S. proposal to Cocom, said the U.S. strategy of
"differentiation" prevailed over West European plans to treat
the Soviet Union and the East European countries essentially
the same way. Cocom's decision to reward the more-democratic
Eastern European countries with higher technology could
induce the Soviets to "move towards the same direction," he
said.
   Mr. Mosbacher said he expects both the former East bloc
nations and U.S. companies to take advantage of the
opportunities being opened. "American companies are going to
leap into Eastern Europe," he predicted. And their presence
could help to "jump-start" those nations' economies.
   The success of the Paris meeting proves that Cocom is
"very much alive," he said. Cocom will have to closely watch
how the special provisions for East Germany work, but after
the two Germanys unite they will be "treated like any other
Cocom member," he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900608-0132
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900608-0132.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   U.S. Forest Service
   Plans a Cutback
   In Logging Allowed
   ----
   By Bruce Ingersoll
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5B
</SO>
<IN>
PULP, PAPER, PACKAGING (ALL TYPES) (PUL)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<GV>
AGRICULTURE DEPARTMENT (AGD)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Forest Service plans a significant
cutback in logging in national forests over the next five
years while putting greater emphasis on recreation and
wildlife protection.
   The annual harvest of timber in national forests averaged
12.2 billion board feet from 1983 through 1988, but it will
fall to 10.8 billion board feet by 1995 under the Forest
Service's new master plan for managing its vast domain of
natural resources. The annual harvest rate won't be restored
to the 12 billion board feet range until the year 2040,
despite a projected 79% increase in demand for hardwoods and
a 35% increase for softwoods by then.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The agency also plans to permit less livestock grazing on
national forest land, an important source of pasture for the
nation's cattle and sheep industries.
   "We are looking at multiple-use management from a new
perspective," said Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter.
"Where timber and mineral production and livestock grazing
cannot be accomplished in an environmentally acceptable
manner, production levels will be reduced."
   Representatives of the timber industry warned that the
plan will only aggravate tight timber supplies, particularly
in the Pacific Northwest. Luke Popovich, spokesman for the
American Forest Council, dismissed the Forest Service's
projections as "essentially useless" because they ignore such
critical factors as the anticipated listing of the rare
northern spotted owl as a threatened species. The industry
fears the listing will trigger logging bans across large
sections of northern California, Oregon and Washington. The
U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service is due to rule on the owl's
status by June 23.
   The Forest Service's five-year plan calls for greater
environmental sensitivity and a better balance among multiple
uses of public lands. Among other things, the agency intends
to permit 49% less clear-cutting of national forests by 1995.
   Clear-cutting, unlike selective cutting of trees, is
regarded as environmentally harmful because it causes soil
erosion and destroys wildlife habitat. The plan also
strengthens the Forest Service's commitment to protecting
"special places" and expanding wilderness areas.
   Under the new plan, the Forest Service projects its annual
costs will hit $3 billion by 1995. Last year, its programs
cost $2.3 billion. Jobs created by Forest Service activities,
including logging, are expected to total 623,000 by 1995, up
49,000 from 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
