<HL>
   Italy's May Car Sales Slip
</HL>
<DATE>
06/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   FIA F G.VOW EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   MILAN -- Italian car sales were down 1.1% in May from a
year earlier but were still 3.3% higher in the first five
months of 1990 than in the same period in 1989, according to
Anfia, the national association of car manufacturers.
   Anfia said 220,990 cars were sold in May, compared with
223,474 in May 1989. A total of 1,154,290 cars were sold in
the first five months, compared with 1,117,043 a year
earlier. Italian car manufacturers, led by Fiat S.p.A., which
makes Fiat, Lancia and Alfa Romeo autos, accounted for 53% of
the market in May and 54 3/4% in the first five months.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Among foreign makers, Ford Motor Co. led the market in May
with 17,933 units sold and a market share of 8.1%. Volkswagen
AG was second with a 7.17% market share and 15,843 cars sold.
