   Business Brief -- Transcisco Industries Inc.:
   Firm to Make Investment
   In Florida's Piper Aircraft
</HL>
<DATE>
06/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   TNIB
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Transcisco Industries Inc., San Francisco, said it agreed
to make a "substantial" investment in Piper Aircraft Corp.
and to take over Piper's parts-distribution business.
   Transcisco said a letter of intent signed with Piper calls
for Transcisco to form a separate company to take over
Piper's world-wide parts business. Transcisco said the letter
also calls for it to receive warrants to acquire an
unspecified amount of stock in Piper, a troubled Vero Beach,
Fla., maker of small airplanes.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The acquisition of the Piper business, if completed, would
fit into Transcisco's effort to expand transportation
businesses beyond the company's basic rail-equipment
maintenance-and-leasing operations, Transcisco said. More
than 90,000 piper airplanes are flying around the world, it
said, representing a large market for replacement parts.
   The transaction provides the privately held Piper with the
working capital it needs to deliver its order backlog of
aircraft, which Piper estimates at over $200 million, and to
develop new models, Transcisco said. Terms of the proposed
acquisition weren't revealed.
</TEXT>
