<HL>
   U.S. Shelter's Assets
   Would Be Purchased
   Under Planned Pact
</HL>
<DATE>
06/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   Z.PAR B.GBL
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Metropolitan Asset Group Ltd. and Lambert
Brussels Real Estate Corp. agreed to buy the assets of U.S.
Shelter Corp., a troubled Greenville, S.C., real estate
syndicator.
   U.S. Shelter is a publicly held property manager and
savings bank owner. It also is general partner in about 150
real estate limited partnerships that own about 220
properties valued at about $700 million, Metropolitan Asset
Group said. Metropolitan Asset said it is difficult to value
U.S. Shelter's partnership interest in the portfolio, but
that it could be as high as $50 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In addition, U.S. Shelter owns Malibu Savings Bank, a
California thrift with about $170 million in assets that
apparently isn't in compliance with new regulatory capital
requirements. U.S. Shelter also has a mortgage banking unit.
   Metropolitan Asset Group is a real estate investment
banking firm. Lambert Brussels Real Estate is the U.S.
investment arm of Pargesa Holding/Groupe Bruxelles Lambert.
   The pact calls for a Metropolitan Asset Group partnership
to provide a $6 million cash infusion into U.S. Shelter.
Also, Lambert Brussels would convert about 40% of its debt in
U.S. Shelter into equity.
   Lambert Brussels is U.S. Shelter's largest creditor, Mr.
Farkas said. Following the purchase, Metropolitan Asset Group
would hold 65% and Lambert Brussels 25% of the equity in the
new company.
   Mr. Farkas said "the reason we're doing this is to create
the largest real estate investment bank and workout entity in
the country." Mr. Farkas said that he envisions the company
"doing a sort of LBO of real estate limited partnerships."
   In a leveraged buy-out, a small group of investors buys a
company in a transaction financed largely by debt.
Ultimately, the group's borrowings are repaid with funds
generated by the acquired company's operations or sale of its
assets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900608-0057
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900608-0057.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   French Oil Group Set
   To Sell Headquarters,
   Boost Capital Base
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   F.TCF
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   PARIS -- Total-Cie. Francaise des Petroles intends to put
its Paris headquarters up for sale in the near future, but
the oil concern gave no indication of the size of the capital
gain the sale would bring.
   Company Chairman Serge Tchuruk told shareholders that the
oil group also intends to boost its capital base in the near
future, but he declined to reveal the magnitude of the
planned capital increase.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Tchuruk said the group's financial performance since
the beginning of this year has been satisfactory in the
exploration and production sectors, while refining and
distribution businesses have been steady but still below
average industry levels of profitability in Europe.
   Mr. Tchuruk said it is "imperative" for Total to improve
its profitability. He pointed out that last year Total's
profitability, defined by earnings as a percentage of
revenue, was 6.4%, well below the industry average of 9%. He
said it was Total's firm intention to improve the group's
profitability to more than 10%, if possible, within the next
2 1/2 years.
   Answering shareholders' criticism that the group's
dividend has remained unchanged since 1985, Mr. Tchuruk said
Total shareholders fare much better than those of most other
big French groups in terms of dividend as a percentage of
earnings per share.
   In Total's case, this came out at 38% for 1989 compared
with 30% for a sample group of 14 big French industrial
groups, he said. He also noted that Total's shares were
yielding 4.2% on the basis of a share price of around 700
francs ($122.81), compared with 2.6% for the sample group.
   Mr. Tchuruk, who is also Total's chief executive officer,
said the group's 400 million tons of crude-oil reserves in
the Middle East will become an increasingly strategic asset,
as the region will become the key area for the international
oil market.
   He reaffirmed his belief that there is no future for the
petrochemical industry in countries that are oil importers.
But he said Total is studying possible partnerships in the
petrochemical field with concerns from oil producing
countries.
</TEXT>
