<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
06/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   CONAGRA AGREED to acquire Beatrice from KKR for $1.34
billion in cash and stock. The price, half what Beatrice
insiders once hoped for, still gives KKR a 50% annual return
on its investment. If approved by regulators, the deal will
give ConAgra such brands as Hunt's and Wesson, boosting the
food giant's clout in the dry grocery business.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The group seeking to buy UAL promised to pay $9 million to
Gerald Greenwald, the former Chrysler Vice Chairman
spearheading the buy-out, even if the takeover fails.
   ---
   GM won a nearly $1 billion pact to supply
pollution-control and engine-control parts to the Soviets'
biggest auto maker. The five-year accord comes as GM is
waging an aggressive expansion into Eastern Europe.
                                                                                                       

   The U.S. and its Western allies agreed to ease their
embargo on high-technology sales to the East bloc.
   ---
   Fed Vice Chairman Johnson will return to academia when his
term expires Aug. 3, despite the president's apparent
willingness to reappoint him.
   ---
   Chrysler's Iacocca agreed to stay on for an unspecified
period after his contract expires in December 1991. The
departure of his onetime heir apparent prompted the
announcement.
   ---
   Stock prices fell for a third consecutive day, pushing the
Dow Jones Industrial Average down 14.32 points to 2897.33.
Bonds inched higher on evidence of slowing economic growth.
   ---
   Retail sales rose a disappointing 3.5% in May from a year
earlier as cold, wet weather held down results, especially
for summer clothes, outdoor products and air conditioners.
   ---
   Capital spending is expected to rise 6.7% in 1990, less
than the 7.8% increase projected earlier in the year. The
latest survey of businesses reflects uncertainty about the
economy.
   ---
   Columbia S&amp;L's plan to sell its $2.9 billion junk-bond
portfolio includes novel financing terms that are boosting
the sale's chances of success.
   ---
   Schering-Plough's accord to sell Maybelline for $300
million to a group including management collapsed, but
Wasserstein Perella stepped in to buy the cosmetics unit at
the same price.
   ---
   A bill to reregulate cable TV was passed by a Senate panel
after a compromise with the industry unraveled. The
legislation faces many obstacles.
   ---
   Drexel's creditors rejected the parent concern's
reorganization plan, and said they will seek to oust
management and recover executive bonuses.
   ---
   The Chicago Merc agreed to pay a $100,000 penalty for
allegedly failing to report violations by member firms. It is
the second-largest such settlement by a commodity exchange.
   ---
   Grain futures prices jumped as wet weather in the southern
Midwest continued to stall planting.
   ---
   SmithKline named Squibb ex-president Jan Leschly to run
the London-based firm's world-wide drug business, succeeding
John Chappell, who quit over management philosophy.
   ---
   TRW's $736 million project to build a "space tug" to boost
satellites into higher orbits was canceled by NASA.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 160,420,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2897.33, off 14.32; transportation 1208.58, off 4.19;
utilities 213.91, off 0.63.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3427.36, up
6.88.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.74, up 0.33; spot
index 132.54, off 0.61.
   Dollar: 152.55 yen, off 0.10; 1.6935 marks, up 0.0050.
