<HL>
   U.S. Auto Makers Set
   2.3% Rise in Output
   For Current Week
</HL>
<DATE>
06/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   GM F C HMC NSANY J.MZD J.MOT TOYOY SBRU J.IZM
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   DETROIT -- The 10 major U.S. auto makers planned to build
143,755 cars this week, a 2.3% increase from 140,505 a year
ago. But for the month of May, U.S. car and truck output fell
16.9% to 874,443 vehicles from 1,051,850 a year ago.
   U.S. car output dropped 7.6% in May, while truck and bus
production was down 33.7% compared with the year-earlier
month.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Separately, auto makers said all car assembly plants in
the U.S. will operate next week, with several working
overtime.
   General Motors Corp. said it has scheduled Saturday
overtime at its Lordstown, Ohio, assembly plant.
   Ford Motor Co. has scheduled Saturday overtime at its
Kansas City, Mo., and Louisville, Ky., truck plants, and
daily overtime at its car plants in Wixom and Wayne, Mich.
   Chrysler Corp. said it has planned overtime at its St.
Louis II, Sterling Heights and Warren, Mich., factories.
