<DOCNO>
WSJ900608-0031
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900608-0031.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Kraft's Italian Unit
   To Take Major Stake
   In Holding Company
</HL>
<DATE>
06/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5B
</SO>
<CO>
   MO
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   MILAN, Italy -- The Italian subsidiary of U.S. food
company Kraft General Foods Inc. is to take a majority stake
in a new holding company being set up to control the Pietro
Negroni S.p.A. salami and cold meats group.
   Kraft General Foods is a unit of Philip Morris Cos.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The accord with Negroni strengthens Kraft's position in
the Italian market while giving the privately owned Negroni
group access to Kraft's financial and technological
resources, top executives of both companies said.
   Under the agreement, Kraft General Foods Italia S.p.A.
will take an approximately two-thirds stake in the new
holding company. (Kraft already has a 25% stake in Negroni.)
The Negroni family, which has been in the prepared-meats
business since 1907, will have a one-third stake in the new
company.
   "The aim is to create an Italian meat concern to compete
better internationally. . . . It is useful to combine forces
to develop the company," said Negroni Chairman Pietro
Negroni, noting that exports would be targeted particularly
at the European and North American markets. The new holding
company is likely to be called Negroni Holding '93.
   Kraft General Foods Italia Chairman Ernesto Fugazzola
would give no details of the cost to Kraft of the
transaction, but said that it had been calculated on the same
basis as other recent transactions in the sector. Despite its
minority stake, the Negroni family will have considerable
influence on the board of the new holding company, especially
concerning strategic investments.
   Mr. Fugazzola said the holding company could eventually be
listed on the Milan stock exchange, although there were no
plans at present for such a step.
   Kraft has been active in Italy for more than 25 years.
Last year, Kraft's Italian unit reported after-tax operating
profit of 77 billion lire ($62.2 million) on sales of 1.22
trillion lire. Employing close to 4,000 people, its main
products include mayonnaise, cheeses, prepared plates, tuna
and pasta.
   Negroni is considerably smaller, with after-tax operating
profit of 1.5 billion lire last year on sales of 140.6
billion lire, and around 800 employees. Its production,
concentrated in four sites around Parma and Cremona in
northern Italy, consists primarily of salami, ham, cold meats
and stuffed pasta.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900608-0030
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900608-0030.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Rockwell Realigns
   Its Big Defense
   Electronics Sector
   ----
   By Rick Wartzman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5C
</SO>
<CO>
   ROK FREST GD
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<LP>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. -- Rockwell International Corp., trying
to squeeze what it can from one of the only potential growth
areas left in the military budget, has realigned its
defense-electronics organization.
   The action won't affect the 16,000 employees in the
sector. But it streamlines the number of divisions that fall
under Rockwell's defense-electronics rubric to five from six,
and the number of individual operating segments to 14 from
17.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "We're always looking for ways to bring like businesses
together, to build on each other," Kent Black, Rockwell's
executive vice president and chief operating officer, said in
an interview. He said the move was made not to save money per
se, but to allow the company to bid more effectively on
Pentagon contracts and overseas work.
   For example, the segment that makes missile-guidance
equipment will be combined with the shop that designs
navigational gear for submarines, allowing the two to share
similar ideas and technologies. Likewise, units that deal
heavily with computer software will unite.
   The push to regroup defense-electronics apparently was
heightened by several recent contract awards. "It's created
pressure to rationalize some of these things," Mr. Black
said. Among the wins: exclusive production of the Hellfire
missile, which had been shared with Martin Marietta Corp.;
the manufacture of parts for the MX and Midgetman missiles,
which had been handled primarily by Northrop Corp.; and the
integration of a combat system for the Australian navy's new
submarine program.
   Mr. Black also said the company has been notified that it
beat out General Dynamics Corp. for a $150 million pact to
upgrade the avionics on F-111 aircraft for the Australian
government, though the contract award hasn't been officially
announced.
   Rockwell's efforts in the defense-electronics realm mirror
those under way throughout the industry. Electronics is one
of the few parts of the Defense Department budget that might
grow through the mid-1990s, because even if new aircraft,
armored vehicles and ships aren't built, the insides of the
older models will have to be retrofitted.
   As a result, competition is heating up. "A lot of
companies are trying to eliminate their redundancies," said
Chuck Quinn, a marketing executive with United Research, a
consulting firm that works closely with aerospace concerns.
Abeyance, he said, will spell doom.
   Mr. Black said he thinks that Rockwell's
defense-electronics group, which now accounts for about 15%
of the diversified parent corporation's $12.52 billion in
total revenue, could expand slightly in the next few years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900608-0029
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900608-0029.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   General Cinema Says
   Second-Quarter Net
   Fell to $29.8 Million
</HL>
<DATE>
06/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5C
</SO>
<CO>
   GCN
</CO>
<IN>
SPECIALTY APPAREL RETAILERS (SAP)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   CHESTNUT HILL, Mass. -- General Cinema Corp. reported a
97% drop in fiscal second-quarter net income, chiefly because
of a gain in the year-earlier period from discontinued
operations.
   The operator of cinemas and specialty retailer said net
for the quarter ended April 30 fell to $29.8 million, or 40
cents a share, from $893.9 million, or $12.10 a share, in the
year-ago period.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The latest period included a pretax gain of $587,000 on
the sale of securities. A year ago, the company had a pretax
gain of $27.1 million on the sale of securities, and had
profit of $859 million from discontinued operations, which
included $855.1 million from the disposal of operations.
Profit from continuing operations was $34.9 million, or 47
cents a share, a year ago.
   Revenue rose 20% to $642.8 million from $536.9 million.
   In the first six months, net fell 95% to $49.9 million, or
68 cents a share, from $938.3 million, or $12.71 a share, in
the year-ago period.
   The latest period included a pretax loss of $586,000 from
the sale of securities. A year ago, the company had a pretax
gain of $82.9 million from the sale of securities, and profit
from continuing operations of $72.4 million, or 98 cents a
share.
   Revenue was $1.16 billion, up 19% from $976.6 million.
   The company did not predict results for the third quarter,
but said it is unlikely its theater division's earnings will
exceed the $12.2 million earned in the past year's summer
quarter.
</TEXT>
